🔍 What Problem Promises Solve

Before promises, JavaScript handled async tasks using callbacks, which often led to:

Callback hell (deep nesting)
Hard-to-read code
Difficult error handling
Poor maintainability

👉 Promises solve this by:

Making async code cleaner and more readable
Providing structured error handling
Avoiding excessive nesting

💡 What is a Promise?
A Promise represents a future value.
👉 Think of it like:
“I promise to give you a result later — either success or failure.”


🔄 Promise States
A promise has 3 states:
Pending ⏳
Initial state
Operation is still running
Fulfilled ✅
Operation completed successfully
Returns a value
Rejected ❌
Operation failed
Returns an error


🔁 Basic Promise Lifecycle
        [ Pending ]
             |
     -----------------
     |               |
[ Fulfilled ]   [ Rejected ]
     |               |
   then()          catch()

👉 Once a promise is fulfilled or rejected, it is settled and cannot change.


⚙️ Creating a Promise

const myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let success = true;

    if (success) {
        resolve("Task completed!");
    } else {
        reject("Something went wrong!");
    }
});

🎯 Handling Success and Failure

myPromise
    .then(result => {
        console.log(result); // success
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.log(error); // failure
    })
    .finally(() => {
        console.log("Done!");
    });


🧠 Key Points:
.then() → handles success
.catch() → handles errors
.finally() → runs no matter what


🔗 Promise Chaining Concept
Promises allow chaining to avoid nesting:
fetchData()
    .then(data => {
        return processData(data);
    })
    .then(processed => {
        return saveData(processed);
    })
    .then(result => {
        console.log(result);
    })
    .catch(err => {
        console.error(err);
    });

Each .then() returns a new promise, enabling chaining.

🔄 Promises vs Callbacks
❌ Callback Style (Hard to Read)

getData(function(data) {
    processData(data, function(result) {
        saveData(result, function(final) {
            console.log(final);
        });
    });
});

✅ Promise Style (Cleaner)
getData()
    .then(processData)
    .then(saveData)
    .then(console.log)
    .catch(console.error);

| Feature         | Callbacks ❌   | Promises ✅   |
| --------------- | ------------- | ------------ |
| Readability     | Poor (nested) | Clean (flat) |
| Error Handling  | Difficult     | Centralized  |
| Maintainability | Low           | High         |
| Chaining        | No            | Yes          |


        Start
          |
       Pending
       /     \
Success       Failure
  |             |
then()        catch()
      \       /
       finally()


Full Promise Example -
const orderFood = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let restaurantOpen = true;

    setTimeout(() => {
        if (restaurantOpen) {
            resolve("🍕 Your order is ready!");
        } else {
            reject("❌ Restaurant is closed!");
        }
    }, 2000);
});

orderFood
    .then(result => {
        console.log("SUCCESS:", result);  //orderFood.then(console.log);
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.log("ERROR:", error);
    })
    .finally(() => {
        console.log("Process finished (either success or failure)");
    });


🔍 What’s Happening
1. Promise Creation
resolve() → called when task succeeds
reject() → called when task fails

2. Handling Result
.then() → runs if resolved
.catch() → runs if rejected
.finally() → runs always


Promise starts → Pending
        ↓
   resolve() OR reject()
        ↓
   then()   OR   catch()
        ↓
        finally()
